articles.author: Howard Schneider, Michael Derby
articles.description: The U.S. economy's strength and continued tight labor markets could require still tougher borrowing conditions to control inflation, Fed Chair Jerome Powell said on Thursday, though rising market interest rates could make action by the central bank itself less necessary.
articles.title: Powell: Strong economy may need more restraint, but bond markets are helping

articles.author: Saqib Ahmed
articles.description: Relentless selling of U.S. government bonds has brought Treasury yields to their highest level in more than a decade and a half, roiling everything from stocks to the real estate market.
articles.title: Falling stocks, climbing mortgage rates: how 5% Treasury yields could roil markets

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: China will require export permits for some graphite products from Dec. 1 to protect national security, the commerce ministry said on Friday, in the latest move to control supplies of critical raw materials.
articles.title: China to require export permits on some graphite products from Dec 1

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: China kept its benchmark lending rates unchanged at the monthly fixing on Friday, matching market expectations, as a set of economic data suggested the economy is stabilising and a weaker yuan constrained further monetary easing.
articles.title: China leaves benchmark lending rates unchanged as expected

articles.author: Leika Kihara, Takahiko Wada
articles.description: Japan's core inflation in September slowed below the 3% threshold for the first time in over a year but stayed above the central bank target, keeping alive expectations that policymakers will phase out ultra-easy monetary policy.
articles.title: Japan's core inflation slows below 3% for first time in over a year

articles.author: David Shepardson
articles.description: United Auto Workers union members who went on strike at Mercedes-supplier ZF's plant in Alabama last month demanding higher pay and better healthcare benefits ended a nearly month-long walkout on Thursday.
articles.title: UAW workers at ZF plant in Alabama ratify labor deal, end strike

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Japan's Toyota Motor (7203.T), the world's largest automaker by sales, said on Thursday it had signed an agreement to adopt Tesla's (TSLA.O) electric-vehicle charging technology from 2025.
articles.title: Toyota to adopt Tesla EV charging standard from 2025

articles.author: Steve Holland, Nidal Al-Mughrabi, Emily Rose
articles.description: President Joe Biden on Thursday asked Americans to spend billions more dollars to help Israel fight Hamas while Israel's defence chief told his troops to be ready to go into the Gaza Strip to destroy the Palestinian militant group.
articles.title: Biden to seek billions in military aid for Israel as invasion of Gaza nears

articles.author: Idrees Ali, Costas Pitas
articles.description: A U.S. Navy warship on Thursday intercepted three cruise missiles and several drones launched by the Iran-aligned Houthi movement from Yemen potentially toward Israel, the Pentagon said.
articles.title: US Navy warship near Yemen intercepted projectiles, Pentagon says

articles.author: Hyonhee Shin
articles.description: North Korean leader Kim Jong Un expressed his resolve to fulfil agreements made at his summit last month with Russian President Vladimir Putin as he met visiting Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov, state media KCNA reported on Friday.
articles.title: North Korea's Kim vows to 'faithfully' fulfil agreements made with Russia's Putin
